```class Solution:
    def decrypt(self, code: List[int], k: int) -> List[int]:
        if k==0: return [0 for i in code]
        temp = code
        code = code*2
        for i in range(len(temp)):
            if k>0:
                temp[i] = sum(code[i+1:i+k+1])
            else:
                temp[i] = sum(code[i+len(temp)+k:i+len(temp)])
        return temp

To deal with this kind of problem, we need to play with the index wisely and carefully, just like defusing a bomb (lol). There are 3 points we need to notice:

0. We need to return the result directly if k == 0 based on the problem statement. (I will handle this case specifically, to make it more readable and slightly faster :) )
1. We need to do ***%*** to make sure the index is always in-bound when k > 0;
2. We need to do ***+code.length*** to make sure it is alway > 0, and ***%*** to make sure the index is always in-bound when k < 0.

Here is my code: 
```
public int[] decrypt(int[] code, int k) {
	int[] result = new int[code.length];
	if (k == 0) {
		return result;
	}
	for (int i = 0; i < result.length; i++) {
		if (k > 0) {
			for (int j = i + 1; j < i + k + 1; j++) {
				result[i] += code[j % code.length];
			}
		} else {
			for (int j = i - 1; j > i + k - 1; j--) {
				result[i] += code[(j + code.length) % code.length];
			}
		}
	}
	return result;        
}
```

