solutions.content:
# Intuition
k is basically a window of elements and we see this window moving across as we move ahead to populate our indices in the new array.

# Approach
We break down the problem into 3 parts. k==0 is straight forward. Our window slides for K>0 and K<0. the movement of the window is same, its just the starting and ending indices we have to identify for the different tow different cases of k. Once we do that we just create a for loop where we slide our window.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n)

- Space complexity:
O(n) and I believe it can't be lower than that as we are supposed to return an array and we should always create a new one rather than modifying our input unless asked to.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int[] decrypt(int[] code, int k) {
        int[] arr = new int[code.length];
        int sumArr = 0;
        int startIndex = 0;
        int endIndex = 0;

        // when K=0 return the array as it is.

        if(k==0){
            return arr;
        }

        // when K>0 , identify the start and end index of the window.
        if(k>0){
            startIndex = 1;
            endIndex = k;
            for(int i=startIndex;i<=endIndex;i++){
                sumArr = sumArr + code[i];
            }
        }

        // when K>0 , identify the start and end index of the window.
        if(k<0){
            startIndex = code.length+k;
            endIndex = code.length-1;
            for(int i=startIndex;i<=endIndex;i++){
                sumArr = sumArr + code[i];
            }
        }

        // Now we just populate each index in the new array. while also incrementing our start and end index.
        for(int i = 0; i<code.length; i++){
            arr[i] = sumArr;

            // if the pointer reaches the end, it comes back from the starting end and hence = 0.
            if(endIndex == code.length-1){
                endIndex = 0;
            }
            else{
                endIndex ++;
            }
            sumArr = sumArr - code[startIndex] + code[endIndex];

            if(startIndex == code.length-1){
                startIndex = 0;
            }
            else{
                startIndex ++;
            }
        }

        return arr;

    }
}
```

