solutions.content:
**Minimization Approach:**

The problem is exactly similar to [926. Flip String to Monotone Increasing](https://leetcode.com/problems/flip-string-to-monotone-increasing/). Its solution is described [here](https://leetcode.com/problems/flip-string-to-monotone-increasing/discuss/1395348/C++-Solution-O(N)).


```
Here we have to delete char from string such that there is no i<j and s[j]=a and s[i]=b means we have to
delete chars to make it monotonic increasing from a to b which is same as monotonic increasing of binary
string where a=0 and b=1. Also flipping 0 to 1 and 1 to 0 can be equally considered as a delete operation
for this problem. So, we use the same solution approach of 926. Flip String to Monotone Increasing. 
```

Runtime: 84 ms, faster than 90.98% of C++ online submissions for Minimum Deletions to Make String Balanced.
Memory Usage: 22 MB, less than 93.87% of C++ online submissions for Minimum Deletions to Make String Balanced.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumDeletions(string s) {

        int sl = s.length();

        //track number of delete 
        int del = 0;

        // counts prefix bs 
        int b_c = 0;

        for(int i=0;i<sl;i++)
        {
            // need to delete when prefix b exists, otherwise ignore
            if(s[i]=='a')
            {
                if(b_c>0)del++;
                else continue;
            }
            else b_c++; // track prefix 1 count

            // get the minimum between delete and b count
            // if delete > b count then it means there is more suffix a then prefix b
            del = min(del,b_c);
        }

        return del;
    }
};
```

**Maximization Approach:**

```
Another way to think about this problem is finding the Length of Longest Monotonic Increasing
Subsequence. Then the minimum delete will be String Length - Max LMIS. 

Now as there are only 2 char type in the string we can easily calculate the Max LMIS for ending char
a and b. Let they are a_c and b_c. Now the LMIS ending with a must contain all previous 'a' char and
so we just increment its count. Other hand, Max LMIS ending with b can have previous a chars a_c or 
previous Max LMIS of ending with b, b_c and we update b_c as max(a_c,b_c) + 1. The max LMIS will be
the max value between a_c and b_c at last and thus minimum delete will be String Length - Max LMIS.

Example : 

Max LMIS ending with a => "aaaaaaaa"

Max LMIS ending with b => "aaaaaaab"  or "aaaabbb" or "bbbbbbb"
```

Runtime: 88 ms, faster than 81.27% of C++ online submissions for Minimum Deletions to Make String Balanced.
Memory Usage: 22 MB, less than 75.72% of C++ online submissions for Minimum Deletions to Make String Balanced.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumDeletions(string s) {

        int sl = s.length();

        // Length of LMIS ending with a
        int a_c = 0;
        // Length of LMIS ending with a
        int b_c = 0;

        // loop through string and find max LMIS ending with a and b
        for(int i=0;i<sl;i++)
        {
            // Max LMIS ending with a can only have previous a element and so we increment its count
            if(s[i]=='a')a_c++;

            // Max LMIS ending with b can have all previous a element or previous Max LMIS ending with b elements
            // thus we take the max between those and add the current b
            else b_c = max(a_c,b_c) + 1;
        }

        // minimum delete => Total length - Max LMIS => String Length - max(a_c,b_c)
        return sl-max(a_c,b_c);
    }
};
```

